{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_sierra_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492519/1908011901/0317.xml":{"full_text":"GENUINE OPTINISN\nIN ALL SECTIONS\n\u2014Ralph M. Easly\nWonderful Recuperative\nPowers of Business Evi\ndenced After Depression.\nAaa\n\n\nQuick Recovery Should\nDisarm All Feeling of\nNervousness.\n4\nee  stm\u2014r\u2014\nNEW YORK, Jan. .18.\u2014\u201cThe re\ncuperative power of business which\nwr3 evidenced after the financial\ndepression of recent months is the\ngreatest the country has ever expe\nrienced. Busiress is on the mend. In\ndustrial conditions are bettering and\nwill continue to do so. The presperous\nconditions enjoyed before money be\ncame scarce are at hand again and,\n\u201cwhere temporary stringency was in\nevidence, the most enthusiastic opti\nmism prevails.\u201d\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\ni\n\n\n\n\nin these words Ralph M. Easly, chair\nman of tie executive council of the\nNational Civic Federation, described\nthe general sound conditions of busi\nriesg throughout the country. Mr. Easly\nhas exceptional opportunities to feel\nthe pulse of the country, receiving as\nhe does reports of all meetings cf busi\nness men and labor leaders.\n\ni\not}\n\n\ni\nMr. Easly pointed out the fact that\nin recerit years, when depression was\nencountered, at least a year and some\ntimes much longer was required for\nrecovery. Ubserving the distinction be\ntween a panic and a peculiar depres\nsion due to withdrawal of money from\nthe banks, he said it was but natural\nthat the people should quickly right\nconditions and discourage unfounded\nnervousness. The dispatch with which\nhusiness became normal indicates the\nsplendid condition of business-\u2014the\n809d health that heals quickly.\ni EE\ni\n\n\n\n\ni\n\ni p\n\n\n\n\nJ\nLabor Contract Renewals.\n\nMr. Easly said the renewal of con\ntracts between labor organizations and\nemployers is the best indication of the\nrestoration of confidence in the pros\npect of continued prosperity. The build\ning trades, he says, are renewing con\ntracts in New York. The riilroads are\ndoing the same; the longshoremen along\nthe lakes are conferring with employers\nfor a renewal of last vear\u2019s scale. This\nlast is an indication of increased activ\nity in many great industries, principally\nin the iron mines, the lumber business,\nand shipment of grain and flour.\n\n\n\n\nf=\nR\nf\n\n\nin\nWhile some industries, because of\ntemporary lack of currency, have been\ncompelled to run short time, these ara\nfast coming back to a normal state.\nWage cuts are rare, and only such as\ncan be expected during the winter sea\nson.\n\nf\nMr. Easly said that at a meeting of\nthe New England Civie Federation,\nwhich was attended by business men\nand labor leaders from all paris of the\nNew England States, a spirit of opt\nmism prevailed. This meeting was held\nin Boston last week.\n\nA\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nManufacturers Confident.\nThe manufacturers expressed confi\ndence that the industries peculiar to\nthe New England Siates were now on\nthe mend, and the wheels would be\nhumming as busily as ever within a\nshort time.\n\nThroughout the South, Mr. Easly\nsald, conditions are good. The South\ndid not suffer compared with the East\nern section of the country, and condi\ntions are generally good.\n\n\n\nReferring to the fact that only sixty\ndays have elapsed since the people were\nmade nerveus by banking conditions,\nMr. Easly said the recuperation was\nmarvelous, and could mean nothing else\nthan a complete restoration of conti\ndence, which is synonymous with a\ncondition of prosperity. Golden streams\nare pouring into the savings banks,\nthus attesting to individual prosperity\nthrouzhout the nation, and while this\nlasts cenfidence cannot be shaken.\n\n\nn i\n\nWashington Free\n\nFrom Hard <imes\nA, Lisner\nA. Lisner, proprietor of the Palais\nRoyal, says that 1907 was the Lest year\nhis establishment has ever had and that\nLe expects better results from 1908.\n\n\n\nMr. Lisrer adds that he has not no\n\nticed any depression whatever in busi\nness.\n\u201c1 notice.\u201d he says, \u2018\u2018that one of our\nJocal financlers takes a gloomy view of\nthe outlook, but I believe there are no\nclouds on the horizon that cannct be\ndissipated. Why should we in Wash\ningten fear hard times?\u201d\ni\nY\ni\ni\n\n1\n1\n\nHosiery Bargains That\n\nMuslin\n1\nCan't Be Egualed\n15\u00a2c Men's Black Sox 73;\u00a2c\n\u00a5ast black Sox that sell\neverywhere for 1ic. Spe\ncial, Tc.\n25c Men's Wool Sox 1134\u00a2c\nAll-wuol Sox 25\u00a2 quality,\nin black, tan, and gray.\nReduced to 11%ec.\nInfants\u2019 19\u00a2 Wool Hose\n83;\u00a2\nClosing out; all ribbed\nwhite and black 18\u00a2 Wool\nInfants\u2019 Hose for 8c\nBoys\u2019 and Girls\u2019 15\u00a2\nHose 93;\u00a2\nSchool Hose, ka 23 double\nknee, heel, and toe; lic\nquality. Special, %94e\u00a2\n\n\n\n=5C. 3\n\n\nExtra Heavy Child's\nHose 12%5\u00a2\n\nRieycle heavy ribhed\nHose, absolutely seamless;\ndouble knee. heel, and toe.\nSpecial, 12%e.\n\u201c5\n15\u00a2 ladies\u2019 black with\nwhite feet or plain Black\nHose, fine Maco yarn. For\na day, 9c.\n\n10\n\n39\u00a2 Silk Lisle Hose 17c\u00a2c\nJust lke silk; gauzy,\nsilky, 3c quality Ladies\u2019\nBlack Hose, reduced price\n17\u00a2, or 3 for 50c.\n\n8\nWUTLOOK FOR PRESENT YEAR BRIGHT IN ALL LINES OF TRADE\n\nCorsets 69\u00a2c\nAll shapes in\nthe _opular $1\nR G Cor\nsets, for a day,\ndc.\n19\u00a2c Side and\nBack Combs 9\u00a2\n\n19\u00a2 Shell and\namber om bs,\nwith polished\nteeth, Sc.\n15\u00a2 No. 40\nTelok Rives\nPink, white,\nblue, black and\nred taffeta rib\nbon, 15\u00a2 width,\nspecial 8%\u00a2c\nAnother Lot of Those\n$4 Cloth Panama Skirts\n$1.98\n$406 and $5.00 black,\nbrown, and blue Panama\nand Wool Melton Skirts,\u201d\nmade in the stylish full\npleated effect with folds,\nfor $1.98. A great bargain.\nThe sale of these last\nwe2k was s0 heavy many of\nour customers were disa\nposated, we now have plen\nor all.\nWashington Business Men\nAre Optimistic in Views\nConcerning 1908 Outlook\n\n\nDry Goods Merchants\nAre Satisfied With the\nProspects for Year.\nReal Estate Men See Rosy\nFuture for Sales of\nCapital Property.\nss\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nSmall Danger- of Finan\ncial Flurry Because of\nFederal Payments.\n\nOptimism based on the cxperience of\nthe past year and the opening of the\nnew year is the keynote struck by most\nWashington business men, in expressing\ntheir opinions concerning the outlook\nfor business this year, as far as Wash\nington is concerned. Wholesale mer\nchants, retailers, and real estate men\nare generally 8 the opinion that the\nyear promises well in their respective\nlines. The consensus of opinion is to\nthe effect that while it would be un\nwise to predict an extraordinarily pros\nperous year, every indication justifies\nthe belief that there is no occasion for\nuneasiness at the present time and that\nno such occasion is likely to arise.\ni\nThe  fact- that Washington is par\nticularly fortunate in this respect is fair\nly conclusively proved by a compari\nson with conditions in other large cities.\nS. H. Ditchett, editor of the Dry Goods\nEconomist, was in the city yesterday\nafter having made a trip covering the\nprincipal cities and some of the smaller\ntowns of the middle West, \u2018including\nCincinnati, Columbus, Akron, Mans\nfield, Cleveland, Chicago, and St. Lous.\nThe purpose of his trip was to dis\ncover by personal observation the exact\ncondition eof business, particularly\namong dry goods merchants, but not\nlimiting himself to that trade alone.\nHe said to a Times reporter at the Ra\nleigh Hotel yesterday that Washington\nis unique as far as business conditions\narc concerned.\n\ni\n\ni\n1\nFound Many Idle People.\n\u201cThere are many idle men and wom\n\u20acn in the towns and cities that I visit\ned,\u201d said he, \u201cand 1 found that mer\nchants were pretty well stocked up. The\neffect of this will be, of course, that\nthere will be decreased consumption by\nthe public and little buying on the part\nof merchants, curtailing business all\nalong the line. I do not believe that\nwe will have a very baa year, never\n\u2018theless, and that 1%8 win compare fa\nvorably generally with 1904 and 1905.\n\u201cIn Washington, however, the condi\ntion is unique. 1 see no evidences of\nr depression here and I can think of no\nreascn why there shourd be. The Gov\nernment is the great foundation om\nwhich stability of business is based in\nWashington. You are fortunate.\u201d\ni ee\n\u201cWe have never before listed so\nmany applications for property during\nthe first half of January. The notice\nable feature is the interest these ap\nplicants take in Washington real estate\nand the earrestness in wishing to in\nvest. Not a few of these have hercto\nfore had their money in stocks, bonds,\nloans, and other forms of security.\nThe financial flurry would seem to have\nbeen a fortunate thing for the real\nastate business, in having diverted\nlarge amounts of money to the real\nestate field.\u201d\ni\nThis is the optimistic view of the real\nestate situation \u2018in Washington, taken\nby Charles Walilroff, secretary and\ntreasurer of Moore Hill, Incorpor\nated.\ni\ni\nCoE ees 0\nWashington Growing.\ni\n\u201cWhy should anyone he otherwise\nthan optimistic regarding the future of\nWashington, and the possibilities and\nprobabilitics of real estate here\u201d he\nadds. \u201cEvery world power capital is\ngrowing at a rapid rate, and the cap\nital of the United States no less than\nany of the others.\n\u201cDespite the recent money stringency,\nthe country is in a mos! prosperous\ncondition. The very stringency has\n9\u00a2 Turkish\nTowels 473\u00a2C\nFair sized\nheavy Turkish\ntoweis, for a\nday, 47gc.\n69c Alligator\nand Morocco\nCarrying Bags\nBrot gray.\nand blk leather\nbags, in 3 dif\nferent shapes,\nfor a dav 25\u00a2.\nUnderwear Values\n75\u00a2 Gowns 471lc\noc Ladies\u2019 lace neck em\npire or embroidered and\ntucked yoke Gowns, good\ncotton, full cut; for a day\nday, 47%c.\n3%\u00a2 Lace Corset Covers 25\u00a2\n39\u00a2 Nainsook Covers, with\n5 rows of lace and 3 strips\nof pink or blue baby rib\nbon. For this sale only,\nf\n\u20ac9\u00a2c Skirts 49c\u00a2\n6%\u00a2 full cut, good Muslin\nUnderskirt, with lace edge\nand 1 row of lace inserting.\nFor a day, 49c.\n3%\u00a2 Drawers 25\u00a2\nLadies\u2019 3%\u00a2 Drawers,\neither tucked ruffle or\ntucked with wide lace edge\nOpen or closed. Special,\n25\u00a2 Ladies\u2019 Drawers l4c\nGood Bleached Cotton\nDrawers, with tucked\nruffle. Special, ldc.\n50c Infants\u2019 Drawer\nL.eggins 25c\n#0c Infants\u2019 White Wool\nKnit Drawer Leggings. Re\nduced to 5c.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SUNDAY, JANUARY 19, 1908.\nx\n5\n2\nCHARLES F. WALRAFF,\nI. GOLDENBERG.\nF. P. MAY,\nHARRY KING.\nARTHUR C. MOSES.\nA. LISNER.\neen large!\u00bb due to an excess of busi\nness with 21 amount of circulating\nmedium irsufficient to meet the un\nasual demands.\n\u201cThe crops of the past year make a\nsplendid showing, and with the world's\nmarkets ready to buy at good prices\nthere is ro need tc be troubled. The\nCapital of the United States naturally\nshares in this desirable condition,\nPeculiar Advantage Here,\n\u201cWith $2.4. in cash disbursed each\nmonth to about 25,80 employes of ihe\nGovernment, Washington nas no need\nto fear under any circumstairces local\nfinancial stringency. The happenings of\nthe last few moths throughout the coun\ntry when crip and clearing house certifi\ncates were called into play have ilius\ntrated most forcibly Washington's pecu\nliar advantage; ihis city being practi\ncally the only one that has not had\nto resort to these makeshifts.\ni\n\u201cPeople throug\u00a5yout the country have\ncome to realize the peculiar advantages\nand safety of Washington real estate as\nan invesiment. Weshingion, not being a\n\u2018manufacturing \u00a2commuity, is not subject\nto the depressions that periadically\ncome to such, and the income of iis\nworkers is sure and regular.\u201d\nOthers Are Optimistic.\n\u201cIt's an ill-wind \u2018that blows nobody\ngood\u2019 is the way in which W. R. Wil\ncox, of Wescott, Wilcox Hamme, re\ngards the present financial situation in\nrelation to the real estate market. Mr.\nWilcox takes a decidedly opti\nmistic view of the coming year. He\nbelieves that investors and lenders of\nmoney are turning from stocks to a\nconsiderable extent and selecting good\nBEHREND'S\n722-724 7th St.N. W.,\nitis Our Aim to Give You What You Want in Bargains\nWhen we advertise an article you can rely on it coming up to your expectations, and\nyour purchase we guarantee will be more than satisfactory.\n$1.69 Heatherbloom Skirts, 88c\nBlack Heatherbloom Skirts, Mercerized Satteen Skirts in pretty shades of brown, light\nand dark blue, green, gray, pink, and red; made with extra wide full pleated ruffie and dust\nruffle. Reduced price 2S8c.\nRemarkatly Low Prices Prevail in Our Suit Department\n$5.00 gray mixed Panama $5.00 Chiffon Panama Coat Suits $4.92 i\nkirts ful nleated witl two Odd sizes of Black and\nShires, Jo fry 5. ve ca Baris id Fancy Suits that sold up to\nfolds of silk taffeta; all seams Greatest cut price\u2014All-wool $12.00, Final closing out price,\ntaped. For this sale only $1.35. Brown, Black and Blue Pana- #98 3\nma Skirts, full Xilted effect, $16 Black Coat Suits $3.95\n$4.98 for All-silk Lined that sold for $5.00, Closing All Wool Black Suits, in the\na ack Thibet Coats rice \u00a32 70 stylish prince chap style, lined\nYang Bem g: price $2.29. throughout in silk, full kilted\nskirt with fold. Closing out\nprice, $8.95.\nCoats left, G-inch long,\nBlack Thibet Coats that sold $6.00 Silk Fold Panama\nfor $15.09; all silk lined. Clos- Skirts $3.85\nin yut price, $4.98\ning out price, $4.98, We invite your comparing 62\u00a2c Long Lisle Gloves 25\u00a2\n\nhis with anv 3588 Black, White, and Gray Long\n$10.00 Short Jackets $2.98 this with any. 35.98 Skirt you yi. \"Gloves, for a day, 25c.\na have ever scen; all wool chif\n5 Coats left, Short Silk Lined \u00a25,, panama, with 5-inch fold 15\u00a2 Children's Ribbed\nTan Melton Cloth Jackets that SE Sill Ti s Drawer Bodies 83;\u00a2\nsold for $10.00. Closing out of taffeta silk: all colors. Spe- All sizes up to 12 years! 15\u00a2\nprice, $2.98. cial price, $3.25. ribbed drawer bodies, 8%c.\nreal estate and real estate loans in\npreference,\n\u201cEntirely aside from spe-~ulative mat.\nters,\u201d says he, \u2018the recent contraction\nand depression is having the effect, in\n4 measure, of kessening the popularity\nof stocks as investments and as se\ncurity for loans, and enhancing the fa\nvor in which good real estate is held\nfor these purposes. The person who\nhas his money invested in good real es\ntate or has it loaned out on ~anilar\nsecurity need not lie awake nigh.; wor\nrying over a possible deureeiation in his\ninvestment or security. Real estate is\nthe basis practically of all values, and\nfor this reason I look for a very good\nyear.\n\u201cAnother reason on which I base this\nopinion is that the lull in building op\nerations particularly will give the de\nmand for building an opportunity to\ncaiwh up with the supply, which, per\nhaps, has been slightly in advance of\nactual needs, and the consequent ac\ntivity will, therefore, be perfectly\nhealthy. 1 see no reason for taking any\nother than an optimistic view of the\noutiook for the year.\u201d\nCapital Outlook\nContinues Normal,\nSays Goldenberg\nI. Goldenberg, of the firm of M. Gold\nenberg, reports that there has been no\ncessation in the normal volume of busi\nness and does not anticipate any. The\nstore was so crowded with customers\nwhen a reporter called sesterday that\nity was some time before Mr. Golden\nberg could be located. He unhesi\ntatingly answered the query as to the\nbusiness outlook for the merchant for\nthe year with the statement that no\nrezson cxisted for a belief in any o\u2019her\nthan a bright future.\n\u201cI think,\u201d said he, *\u2018that the so-calied\npanic and depression has been one of\ntalk rather than of actual existence. At\nany rate, it is not evident in Washington\nand no disturbance need he feared.\u201d\nWASHINGTON BANKS\nSEE IMPROVEMENT\nIN FINANCIAL CIRGLE\nCapital\u2019 Not Affected by\nRecent Stringency in\nMarket\nWashington financial institutions are\n\u2014\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014tth\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nbeginning to feel the improvement in\nbusiness conditions, following the return\nof confidence and the restoration of\nnormal conditions in large financial cen\nters,\nThe final showing of profits from the\nbusiness of 1997 indicated plainly the\nloss of much interest during the months\nof December and Newember. At this\ntime the bankers of this and all other\ncities were using their every efforts to\naccumulate cash gnd their reserves were\nentirely out of proportion to what they\nshould or would have been in normal\ntimes.\nSo far as Washington was concerned\nthere were no runs, no wild clamor for\nmoney, and practically no great uneasi\nness. It would have been remarkable\nhad there b:en no uneasiness, but with\nbanks failing all cver the couniry and\nwilh nervous, anxious humarity, in re.\nceipt of harrowing stories of currency\nfamine in other cities, it was not to be\nexpected that there would be no cur\nrency withdrawals\u2014but they were not\nthe rule. But our bankers were pre.\npared for the wesrst and ready to stand\na run, which, fortunately, they escaped.\nBecause of this idle money, held against\npossible exigency, they did not make\ntheir usual profits.\nBut they did, even in the most strenu\nous days of the panic, care for their\ncustomers\u2019 interest, just as they are do\ning now. They re nct.over-generous,\nthey are not foreing loans or accommo\ndations on thelr customers, but where\na legitimate loan is needed it will be\nforthcoming.\nThe unseasonable weather has been\nagainst trade in general, especially since\nthe hclidays, and many concerns are\ncomplaining of the lack of demand for\nseasonable goods, or what are usually\nso considered at this season of the year.\n\u2018There has been some improvement in\nthis demand during the last week and\nit begins ta look as if the concessions\nin prices would close out stocks.\ni\nWhile Washington bankers are letting\nout money more freely they are\ndoing nothing to advance the cause of\nWall Street, nor have they extended\ntheir\u2019 bounty beyond the range of their\ncustomers. Moreover, the scrutiny of\ncoliateral is still kept up. i\nSaid President Bell, of the American\nSecurity and Trust Company: \u201cWe are\nlooking forward to a better demand for\nmoney and perhaps better rates. Busi\nress is picking up and we will be able\nto put more of our money into use.\nConditions are getting better every\nwhere\nCashier Ruff, of the Nationa! Metro\npolitan Bank, said: *\u201c\u201cWe recognize the\nfact that the financial situation is very\nmuch better. We, like other national\nbanks of this city, have been carrying\ntoo heavy reserves and yet it was the\npart of wisdofn. General business is\npicking up. More seasonable weather\nwould be welcomed by our merchants,\nas it would help them dispose of the\nlast of their winter goods. People have\nfelt and acted economically, as a result\nof the panic, and yet Washington knew\nlittle of it, save through the stories in\nnewspapers. We look for steady im\nprovement.\u201d\nBusiness on the Washington Stock Ex\nchange has shown a meiked improve\n\u2018ment during the last few weeks, and\nims is likely continue Jor an indefin\nite period. 'liie fact that lccal interests\nare dominant in Washington Railway\nand Electric Companv\u2019's affairs is an\nexcellent thing for <r: stock of this\ncompany. It inspires coriidence among\nstockholdere, and intend ng investors\ncoasider it a favorable move. More\nover the ponds of the comrpany are con\nsidered a safe investment and are much\nmore popular than they were before the\ncertainty of the election of the I.oeb\nboard of directors.\nCommenting on this matter, Secretary\nWoodruff of the Stock Exchange, said:\n\u201cThe fact that our other traction com\npany has passed into the hands of local\ninterests has caused a good investment\ndemand for the bonds and stock of the\ncompany.\n\u201cOther Washington stocks offer good\nopportunities for investment, and, just\nso soon as the uncertainty in the local\ngas situation has been removed by a de\ncision in the case now before the court,\nthere should be much trading in gas\nstocks. It must be remembered that\nWashington stocks did not suffer to\nanything like the extent that New Yeork\nstocks did in the panic, and, th\u00aeefore,\ntaey wili not have such radical ad\nvances. but they should improve ma\nterially.\u201d\nProtected Customers.\nMore Manufacturing Needed\nTo Keep Young Men at Home\nA Necessity, Says A. C. Moses\nee emt tn A Sm\nA brighier year for Washington in\ndustrially is the alm of the manufaetur\ning committee of the Chamber of Com.\nmerce. That not only 1503 shall witness\nan incre. se in the growth of industrial\nWashington, but that each succeeding\nyear stall also show a decided increase\nnot only in th. buginess of those fac\ntories already established, but in the\nnumber of factories in the District, is\nto be the object of special cfforts on\nthe part of the committes,\nWashington hes had a good year,\nnew factories and warenouses combined\nhave been projected within\u2019 the pasi\nfew months, and scme of them: are now\nbuilding.\u201d There has been no industrizl\ndepression In the District, and none is\nInoked for. The condition is one of re\ncz3gary expansion, rather than.contrac\ntion. None of the half-time and reduced\npay conditions that obtain elsewhere\nin industrial centers are experienced\nhere,\nArthur C. Moses, chairman of the\nmanufactures committee, is determined\nthat there shall be an increase of in\ndustry in the District. He and other\nBusiness Fine\nAll Over South,\nSays F. P. May\nWashington jobbers have little of\nwhich to complain respecting busi\nress as it is and as it promises to be\nduring the year. F. P. May, of the F.\nP. May Hardware Company, one of the\nlargest whelesale hardware houses in\nthe South, contributes a very encour\naging report. While he is not given to\noverstating conditions he says that a\nvery much better condition now exists\nin the countrv than had been expected.\n\u201cOur salesraen are sending In a very\nsatisfactory volume of orders and I\nlook for a normal spring business. Not\nonly are we receiving good orders, \"bul\nwe have no complaint to make in ref\nerence to cn'*ections. The people of\n\u2018he South, in which our territory prin\ncipally is, seem to have plenty of\nmoney with which to meet their bills\npromptly. Altogether the wholesale\nsituation is very encouraging.\u201d\nMoney Sttingency\nRich Man's Panic,\nSays Harry King\nHarry King, of King's Palace, adas\nhis voice to the chorus of thove onti\nmistically disposed. Wken a Times ie\nporter cailed upon him vesterday after\nnoon Mr. King explained that he nad\njust returned from: a business trip to\nGREATER AND BETTER YEAR\nLOOKED FOR BY BUILDERS\nOptimism promising much for the In\ndustrial progress of Washingion during\n1908 pervades (he ranks of its repre\nsentative coniractors and builders.\nDespite the recant financial flurries,\nwhich necessarily affect larger enter\nprises, there is already promised enous!\nto make the year a notable one in th:\nrea ms of architecture.\nA canvass of the men who direct the\ntransferring of stone and steel and lum\nber into the magnificent structures that\nare now springing up on almost every\nhand, reveals that it is rather early to\nobtain a complete index of what the\nyear really holds in a constructive line.\nNevertheless there is contemplated and\nunder way a sufficient number of build.\nings to indicate that the record of 1908\nwill surpass any yet made in the Capital\nof the Naticn.\nThe vear will see the completion of\na greater number of magnificent Govern\nment buildings than has ever ye!\nmarked any one year in the city\u2019s his.\ntory. This in itself means the release\nof millions of dollars, which will flow\nthrough every artery of the city\u2019s trade\nLooking forward at the undertakings\nvet to be begun, the new $700,000 home\nof the Bureau of American Republics,\nwhich will be under way before the\n10c Embroid\nered Turnover\nCollars 47gc\nEmbroidered\nand hemstitch\ned turnovers\nthat sell regu\nlarly for loc,\nspecial 4%e.\n$1.75 Lace\nCurtains 95\u00a2\n32 yd. long\nNottingham White Bodyj\u00a7\nlace curtain, skirts of flan\nrich heavy de-}nelette that sell\nsign. Special regularly fo r\n98c. uc, special 25\u00a2.\nWaists\nOur new spring styles\nhave arrived, allowing us\nto offer big selections at\nlow prices,\n$1.69 and $1.98 Persian\nLawn Waists 98\u00a2\n19 styles to choose from\u2014\nwhite Swiss waist with 9\nrows of 2-inch Fill\u00e9 lace in\nfront, back and sleeves \u2018an\nallover lace waist); worth\n$2.00. For this sale only\n98c. Also allover Embroid\nered Waists and magnifi\ncent styles of Lace Waists;\nnone worth less than $1.69.\nFor this sale only, 8c.\n$3.50 Lace Waists $1.95\nWhite and Ecru Net\n Waists, with silk founda\ntions, silk embroidered\nfronts; banded with taffeta\n\u00abilk; an exquisite effect.\nVery special, $1.8.\n47%c\nfor white madras black\n\u2018sateen, percalg, and ging\nham waists, that seld up\nto Tc. Very special for\n$5 Children\u2019s Coats $2.69\nLast cut -on Children\u2019s\n\u201cCoats. Any coat that sold\nup to $5.00, of red, blue,\nand hrown ziheline. 8Ki~-=\nto 14 years. Cut price, $2.08.\nBargain Sale of Bed Wear\n65\u00a2c White Bed Spreads,\nfull size, very pretty pat\nterns and taped edges.\nSpecial, 37%c.\n15\u00a2 Pillow Cases 1lligo\nlL.argest size best cotton\nPillow Cases, with deep\nhem, regular 15\u00a2 quality.\nReduced to 11%zc.\